-- tCheap Talk on a Grand Scale -- tJournalism and the Press -- tPublic Opinion and the Crowd -- tAdvertising and Impression Management -- tPolitics, Revolution, and Reform -- tEquality -- tEconomics -- tPsychological Analysis -- tBehavior Change -- tAnxiety, Guilt, and Boredom -- tContradictions within Academia -- tEducation and the Universities -- tPhilosophical Systems -- tPure Thought -- tDoubt -- tSpeculation and Idealism -- tSocrates -- tTeaching -- tAppendix: How Comic Episodes Correlate with the Stages -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWho might reasonably be nominated as the funniest philosopher of all time? With this anthology, Thomas Oden provisionally declares Søren Aabye Kierkegaard (1813-1855)--despite his enduring stereotype as the melancholy, despairing Dane--as, among philosophers, the most amusing. Kierkegaard not only explored comic perception to its depths but also practiced the art of comedy as astutely as any writer of his time. This collection shows how his theory of comedy is integrated into his practice of comic perception, and how both are integral to his entire authorship. Kierkegaard's humor ranges from the droll to the rollicking; from farce to intricate, subtle analysis; from nimble stories to amusing aphorisms. In these pages you are invited to meet the wife of an author who burned her husband's manuscript and a businessman who, even with an abundance of calling cards, forgot his own name. You will hear of an interminable vacillator whom archeologists found still pacing thousands of years later, trying to come to a decision. Then there is the emperor who became a barkeeper in order to stay in the know. The Humor of Kierkegaard is for anyone ready to be amused by human follies. Those new to Kierkegaard will discover a dazzling mind worth meeting. Those already familiar with his theory of comedy will be delighted to see it concisely set forth and exemplified. Others may have read Kierkegaard intensively without having ever really noticed his comic side. Here they will find what they have been missing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aWit and humor. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh  aConstantin Constantius.  aGodthaab.  aHegelian philosophy.  aNicolaus Notabene.  aPhilosophical Fragments.  aQuidam.  aRepetition.  aSocrates.  aacademia.  aactors.  aassistant professors.  abanquets.  abaptism.  abehavioral change.  aclergy.  acontradiction.  acostumes.  aday laborers.  adisciples.  aearnestness.  aethical existence.  aexistence.  afinishing.  afreedom.  ahorses.  aincommensurability.  ainwardness.  alifelong tasks.  alove.  amale vulnerability.  amisunderstanding.  amoney.  apleasure.  aprofessors.  asuffering.  atalkativeness.1 aOden, Thomas C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691216270zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691216270423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691216270.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK